title: For Sale:  UZI- Israeli IMI model 45
postcontent:
This is the IMI model 45. Israeli UZI with with Hebrew markings for full auto, semi-auto, and safe (full-auto has been obviously disabled) on the lower. This model came as the updated version B" but in a factory 45acp. This beautiful firearm is a work of art and a tank at the same time and has been converted to the 9mm already. Semi-automatic with a 16" barrel. It comes with 9- 32 round magazines, 2- 25 round magazines, and 1- 20 round magazine. The 32 round magazines come in 3 German canvas pouches. The UZI also has the wooden furniture but has the folding metal stock on it now. I just took it out this weekend and it shoots flawlessly and accurately. Information I could find explaining the different models.

 The IMI Model A Semi Auto:
IMI produced a semi automatic version of the UZI that was imported into the United States by Action Arms. It had a 16.1" barrel and a folding stock.

 The IMI Model B Semi Auto:
In 1983, IMI replaced the Model A with the Model B. The sights were the most noticeable difference but other small changes were also included.

The IMI Model 45 Semi Auto:
The Model 45 was just a Model B semi automatic in .45 ACP. It can be converted to 9mm by replacing the barrel, bolt and magazine.

title: For Sale:  SALE PENDING -Winchester Model 12, 16 ga., 26" bbl, nickel finish, rebored for 2 3/4" shells.
postcontent:
This is a really beautiful Winchester Model 12, 16 ga., 26" bbl, nickel finish, rebored for 2 3/4" shells and marked accordingly.  This gun was manufactured in 1913.  The nickel finish has a nice patina but remains in generally good shape.  The 26" bbl has a full choke.  You can look at the pictures and tell this gun has been lovingly used... but it remains in good condition.  This beautiful shotgun is one of the owner's favorites!  Item G-25787-1.

Winchester Model 12

Often called the perfect repeater, Winchester’s Model 12 pump-action shotgun distinguished itself on game fields, trap and skeet ranges, and in both World Wars.

Winchester’s Model 12 slide-action shotgun has won the praise of hunters, competitors and soldiers alike during the 90 years and nearly 2 million pieces made since its 1912 introduction. Some of its fans have even gone so far as to agree with the company’s appellation of the gun as “the perfect repeater.”

The Model 12 was initially offered in 20 ga. only, which made it the first Winchester shotgun of that gauge and the first hammerless slide-action repeating shotgun to bear the Winchester logo. Two years after its introduction, it was available in both 12 ga. and 16 ga. The 12-ga. “trench” model with a 20-inch cylinder-bore barrel, perforated cooling sleeve and detachable knife bayonet was introduced in 1917. Without bayonet lug and cooling sleeve, it was listed in the Winchester catalog as the Model 12 Guard and Riot gun. A 28-ga. sporting version came on the market in 1934.

The gun’s basic mechanical layout—credited to design team chief Thomas Crossley Johnson in the company’s post-Browning partnership era—remained virtually unchanged throughout its life. It is of the old school, wherein the bolt locks up to a forged, machined, blued-steel receiver, and walnut serves for the buttstock and slide handle. Numerous machine operations, some complex in nature, were required to produce the receiver, and Winchester boasted that only the best steel alloys then available were used in the gun’s manufacture.

That quality at all costs approach eventually proved the Model 12’s downfall, however, as it collided with the reality of modern-day labor costs and manufacturing methods. Finally, in the late 1960s, the Model 12 was deemed too costly to keep in production. Attempts were later made to reduce its cost of manufacture, and limited sales of original-type guns were offered through the custom shop. By the early ’70s, though, the pump shotgun in general had lost much of its appeal, and the old warhorse was relegated to the heirloom and collectible sector of the market.

Nevertheless, the Model 12 remains beloved by tens of thousands of sportsmen who refuse to retire their “perfect repeaters” or think less of them.

title: For Sale:  An AMERICAN TRUCK FOR AMERICANS! 1969 CHEVY C10 4X4
postcontent:
Up for sale I have a 1969 C10 4x4 that was built for Uncle Sam when the Cold War was on every American's mind, in every American's home and all over the evening news. This beast was designed by Americans who built the Atomic Bomb, built to support our troops, to resupply them in the heat of battle, and to power forward when lives and country are on the line. This truck was forged in the Heartland of America built from recycled tanks and bombers in a time when STEEL was on the road to not just protect you from an accident but survive and drive you home!
Luckily Former President Ronald Reagan ended the Cold War giving us civilians a chance to drive a beast meant for the heat of battle but tame enough for Americas roads.
It's a stick shift built for that farmboy drafted to be a soldier, one who knows his way around mighty machines that tear at the land and feed a hungry country. 
There is no rust or rot as both fear to even try to form, and with its all American STEEL body she's as straight as an Arrow shot from the bow of Geronimo himself.
Born with a 350 V8 there is NO fancy namby pamby computer crap or sensors to choke life from this mighty machine. Which means you can bust out those Craftsman's tools your beautiful wife/girlfriend bought you for Valentines Day as a symbol of love and wrench on her yourself!
Here's a little 411 directly from Chevy on the engine that beats under the hood of this monster:
The L-48 is the original 350 cu in (5.7 L), solely available for 1967 in the Super Sport version of Camaro SS 350 (1967-up) or Chevy II/Nova in '68-79. In '69 it was used in almost all car lines; Camaros, Impalas, El Caminos, Chevelles & Novas. 1969 L-48's use a Hyd Cam, 4bbl Quadrajet carburetor, cast pistons, 4-bolt main casting number 010 Blocks & casting number 041 or 186 heads. Power output was 300HP and 380 lb·ft (520 N·m) torque. Compression ratio was 10.25:1.
Now take a moment to soak all that information in... An engine so powerful that it powered other champions and still does half a century later! We're talking cars with pedigree's only Legend's can drive!
Tear down trees, rip houses from their foundations, cause your neighbor's Prius to spontaneously combust by merely passing him on the freeway. Did I say freeway! That's RIGHT son of Paul Bunyan, drive her on America's freeways and highways! Keeping her away from those commie states who take your hard earned American money.
This is an AMERICAN truck meant for AMERICANS! God fearing, steak eating, gun shooting warriors of the back woods! This is that EMP proof, bullet proof monster to get you out of dodge in! Taking family and gear to your bug out location and doing it in classic style!
Now it's hard to put a price on American muscle like this! But with a growing family I need to pass her on to another worthy red blooded American who can appreciate power. A man or woman able to control this beast and love it as much as I have.
If you think you measure up shoot me an email and I'll introduce you.

Many parts are included along with a bed mounted tool drawer to keep your tow chains, double-bit axe and bowie knife safe in any weather! And the final item that should push you over is a 100 amp alternator pulsating, feeding unimaginable power to your whim! This means you can put a winch on her or install off road lights or anything else your imagination can conjure up!

WHAT ARE YOU WAITING FOR! Americas roads needs you! Your honey do list can finally be completed!
